{  
"response_text":  
"The total number of households following the non-learning E-RO strategy starts around 20 and declines to approximately 10 by the end of the simulation. This decline begins sharply after step 30, likely due to sustained pasture degradation under stochastic rainfall conditions. Early fluctuations between 20-30 households reflect transient resource variability, but a persistent downward trend emerges after step 50, suggesting systematic resource constraints overwhelming the fixed-rules strategy. The final value of ~10 households indicates partial survival, possibly maintained in pasteures with less severe climate impacts. Variance across runs remains moderate throughout, aligning with stochastic rainfall influencing resource dynamics. These trends reflect E-RO agents' inability to adapt herd management to environmental variability, contrasting with learning strategies that likely exploit adaptive adjustments."
}

